Adoption as an alternative to abortion is not well supported by the general Slovenian population, mainly because for many it is perceived as giving baby to strangers. Semen and egg donation, as forms of ART unwelcome in Slovenia, are accepted by only few of respondents, which is also expected taking into account that sperm and egg donations are still disapproved and significantly fewer Slovenian accept sperm donor as a grandfather. Attitudes and opinions of men towards the most controversial reproductive issues (preimplantation genetic diagnosis, embryo selection, non-anonymous donation of gametes) are generally similar to those of respondents in general population, with exception of embryo selection where many men were rather affirmative towards this practice; it is possible that this is determined by older men in this study who are much more involved in the decision of childbearing and have more to say about family forming.

At the same time, one should keep in mind that the discrepancy of men's and women's views on some controversial techniques may be due to different levels of awareness of men and women about the availability of ART technologies, their costs, their extent and side-effects in daily care. For example, respondents reported that Slovenia does not have any measures in place to limit the number of births per family - which is not true - and respondents were much less aware of side-effects of ART when asked than were other respondents they responded on their behalf in the same vignette
